review:
This is a refreshing take on the Spider-Man which we all know and (Generally) love.<br/><br/>Pros;
<ul><li>Argue if you want but Tom Holland is the best all-around Spider-Man. He is an awkward nerdy Peter and also a quirky fun Spider-Man.</li><li>Michael Keaton knocks his 3rd winged role out of the park as the Vulture. Even when he doesn't don the mechanised wing suit he is just as discomforting as Adrian Toomes.</li><li>The supporting cast of Jacob Batalon, RDJ, Jon Favereau, Marisa Tomei &amp; Zendaya as Ned, Tony Stark, Happy Hogan, Aunt May &amp; Michelle are astounding. Each one brimming with their own personalities all with different things to teach Holland's Spider-Man.</li><li>The CGI is really good and works whenever it is used.</li><li>The colour palette used in all scenes all present the tone of the film really well and provide eye candy in an already solid film.</li><li>The score stands out well in a universe where the Avengers theme exists along with GotG soundtracks.</li><li>As usual, the comedy is great and brings life to these films.</li><li>There are a few twists and unexpected appearances throughout.</li></ul><br/><br/>Cons;
<ul><li>Laura Harrier's love interest for Peter Parker is... meh. Plus on Peter's part, you do not buy that this guy is all he thinks about too much.</li><li>There are a couple of continuity errors with the larger MCU which make it irritating when noticed so... eh.</li></ul><br/><br/>Verdict;
Spider-Man Homecoming is a fresh take on a character with a heavily saturated presence in our culture today whilst giving a new perspective of the MCU from the eyes of millennials: thus helping real millennials relate to it.
